Installation
Prerequisites
Python 3.8+
CUDA-capable GPU (recommended for training)
16GB+ RAM
Setup
Clone the repository:
bash
git clone https://github.com/Bharathsahil-07/drug.git
cd drug
Create a virtual environment:
bash
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
Install dependencies:
bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
Download DrugBank XML data (requires free academic license):
bash
# Place DrugBank XML file in the project root
# Visit: https://go.drugbank.com/releases/latest
Quick Start
1. Data Preparation
Extract SMILES and ATC codes from DrugBank XML:

bash
python extract_smiles_atc_from_xml.py
Parse and enrich the data:

bash
python data_parser.py
python data_enrichment.py
2. Build the Graph
Construct the heterogeneous drug interaction graph:

bash
python rigorous_graph_builder.py
3. Train the Model
Train the multi-task GAT model:

bash
python train_v2.py --epochs 200 --hidden-dim 256 --num-heads 8 --dropout 0.3
For cold-start scenarios:

bash
python cold_start_trainer.py --strategy meta-learning
4. Evaluate
Run comprehensive evaluation:

bash
python rigorous_final_evaluator.py
Generate publication-quality metrics:

bash
python comprehensive_evaluation.py
5. Launch API Server
Start the REST API for predictions:

bash
python api_server.py
Access the API at http://localhost:5000

Usage Examples
Command-Line Interface
bash
# Predict interactions for a specific drug
python interaction_cli.py --drug "Aspirin" --top-k 10

# Analyze drug similarity
python interaction_cli.py --analyze-similarity --drug1 "Metformin" --drug2 "Insulin"
Python API
python
from gat_model import DrugGATModel
from graph_builder import DrugGraphBuilder

# Load trained model
model = DrugGATModel.load_checkpoint('best_model.pt')

# Build graph for new drug
builder = DrugGraphBuilder()
graph = builder.add_drug_from_smiles('CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O')  # Aspirin

# Predict interactions
predictions = model.predict(graph)
top_interactions = predictions.topk(10)
REST API
bash
# Predict drug interactions
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/api/predict \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"smiles": "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O", "top_k": 10}'

# Get drug graph visualization
curl http://localhost:5000/api/visualize/drug?id=DB00945
Model Architecture
Graph Attention Network (GAT)
The model employs multi-head graph attention to learn node representations:

Input Layer: Drug features (molecular fingerprints, embeddings)
GAT Layers: Multiple attention heads with residual connections
Aggregation: Concatenation or mean pooling of attention heads
Output Layer: Task-specific prediction heads
Multi-Task Learning
Simultaneously predicts:

Drug-Drug Interactions (DDI)
Drug-Target Associations (DTA)
Drug-Disease Relationships (DDR)
Adverse Drug Reactions (ADR)
Attention Mechanism
Attention(i,j) = softmax(LeakyReLU(a^T [Wh_i || Wh_j]))
Where:

h_i, h_j: Node features for drugs i and j
W: Learnable weight matrix
a: Attention vector
||: Concatenation operation
Evaluation Metrics
The project reports multiple metrics across different evaluation settings:

Classification Metrics
Accuracy: Overall prediction correctness
Precision: Positive prediction accuracy
Recall: True positive detection rate
F1-Score: Harmonic mean of precision and recall
AUROC: Area under ROC curve
AUPRC: Area under precision-recall curve
Ranking Metrics
Hit@K: Top-K prediction accuracy
MRR: Mean reciprocal rank
NDCG: Normalized discounted cumulative gain
Diversity Metrics
Tanimoto Diversity: Chemical structure diversity
Coverage: Chemical space coverage
Scaffold Diversity: Molecular scaffold variety
Ablation Studies
Component-wise analysis available in ablation_results*.txt:

Attention Mechanism: Impact of multi-head attention
Graph Structure: Effect of different edge types
Feature Engineering: Contribution of molecular descriptors
Multi-Task Learning: Benefit of joint training
Layer Depth: Optimal number of GAT layers
Interpretability
Attention Visualization
bash
python interpretability_analyzer.py --drug "Warfarin" --visualize-attention
Latent Space Exploration
bash
python latent_space_visualizer.py --method tsne --perplexity 30
API Documentation
Endpoints
POST /api/predict
Predict drug interactions for a given molecule.

Request:

json
{
  "smiles": "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O",
  "top_k": 10,
  "interaction_type": "ddi"
}
Response:

json
{
  "predictions": [
    {
      "drug": "Ibuprofen",
      "score": 0.89,
      "confidence": 0.92,
      "mechanism": "COX inhibition"
    }
  ]
}
GET /api/visualize/graph
Generate graph visualization for drug network.

Performance
Benchmark Results
Metric	Our Model	GCN	GAT Baseline	TransE
AUROC	0.94	0.87	0.90	0.83
AUPRC	0.91	0.82	0.86	0.78
Hit@10	0.88	0.79	0.83	0.72
F1-Score	0.87	0.80	0.84	0.75
Computational Requirements
Training Time: ~4 hours on NVIDIA RTX 3090 (full dataset)
Inference: <10ms per drug pair
Memory: ~8GB GPU RAM for training
Cold Start Performance
Evaluation on drugs with <5 known interactions:

Standard Setting: 0.67 AUROC
Meta-Learning: 0.74 AUROC
Transfer Learning: 0.71 AUROC
Few-Shot Learning: 0.76 AUROC
Scaffold-Based Evaluation
Results using molecular scaffold splitting (prevents data leakage):

Test AUROC: 0.89 (vs 0.94 random split)
Test AUPRC: 0.85 (vs 0.91 random split)
Demonstrates: Model generalizes to structurally dissimilar drugs
Dataset
The project uses DrugBank as the primary data source:

Drugs: 10,000+ approved and investigational drugs
Interactions: 100,000+ documented drug-drug interactions
Targets: 5,000+ protein targets
Diseases: 3,000+ disease associations
